data.content:
## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread exceeding a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. The fix is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // PITFALL: Always dispose CancellationTokenSource — it leaks
        // timers and callbacks otherwise.
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            // Task.WaitAsync throws TimeoutException if the token
            // fires before the task completes (.NET 6+).
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | If `work()` is a long CPU-bound call that never checks the token, it keeps running after timeout. `Task.Run` only checks the token *before* starting. The timeout above abandons the *wait*, but the work continues on a thread-pool thread. |
| **Truly uncooperative code can't be stopped in-process** | If `work()` is opaque (e.g., third-party library, tight native loop), move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (as shown). Let it propagate elsewhere. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks. |

### If `work` Can Be Modified (Preferred)

Pass the token through so cancellation is truly cooperative:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — token is checked inside the loop:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### What Was Removed

| .NET Framework API | Replacement |
|--------------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — not needed with cooperative model |
| Manual `new Thread()` + `Join(timeout)` | `Task.Run()` + `WaitAsync(token)` |

### Async Alternative

If your codebase is async, prefer the fully async version:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

The critical mental shift: **you can no longer kill a thread from the outside**. The running code must voluntarily check for cancellation. Design checkpoint frequency based on your acceptable cancellation latency.
